(947, 3, '2012-12-04 20:51:26', '2012-12-04 18:51:26', 'BUSINESS: Supervisors Are the Key to Productivity\r\nSouth Africa’s labour productivity has reached a 46-year low according to recent Adcorp figures. This figure can be attributed to a major gap across all South African industries, whereby supervisors lack efficient training and are not properly equipped with the right skillset to fulfill their role.\r\n\r\nThis is the view of Arjen de Bruin, Operations Solutions MD at OIM International - a leading business consultancy firm, who says companies are able to improve productivity levels by an average of 10% to 15%, by ensuring that supervisors receive practical on the floor coaching with relevant training to help them fully understand their role as the drivers of sustainable workforce productivity.\r\n\r\n“The biggest impact on a workforce is the supervisor, as he or she is responsible for managing all processes, removing obstacles and assessing overall workforce productivity. Supervisors therefore need to possess efficient problem solving techniques, plan correctly and be able to communicate daily tasks effectively to the team as these skills are critical for ensuring workforce throughput,” says de Bruin.\r\n\r\nDe Bruins says 80% of a supervisor’s time should be spent ensuring the team is maximizing production output thoroughly each day. “Instead, what we find is that 60% of the time supervisors are busy with passive supervision, admin or HR-related duties and getting involved in production, as there is often a skills deficit and the supervisor has no other choice but to fill the gap. We have also noticed the supervisor fall into a comfort zone with work that is familiar.”\r\n\r\nDe Bruin argues that by working on a supervisor’s key competences, where he plans his day correctly, communicates tasks effectively to his team, takes care of his staff, remove obstacles through problem solving, develops his staff where there are skills lacking; he will become more efficient in carrying out tasks and be able to increase business production.\r\n\r\n“These competencies are the basis of a supervisor’s role and it is therefore important that enough time is invested training supervisors to ensure that they understand them and to ensure they are equipped with the necessary skills. However it is important to note that the time invested in improving people’s skills, must be reflected in increased output and quality. Moreover, by implementing constant performance feedback and measurement, performance will be optimised across the business.”\r\n\r\nDe Bruin says when supervisors and their labour force are provided with structure, alignment and focus in their day-to-day activities, individuals will have a shared purpose and direction of their role. Similarly, for supervisor to be effective leaders, consistent communication and engagement needs to happen in order for them to understand how their roles contribute to the success of the company.\r\n\r\nThese key disciplines need to be integrated into a training programme that combines practical on-the-floor coaching and continuous assessments. De Bruin refers to a pilot project that used this training programme on a South African mine, conducted by OIM International earlier this year. All supervisors of the mine were assigned experienced operational improvement consultants and underwent intense training, on-the-floor coaching and practical assessments. Supervisors were observed, coached and together with the consultant co-created operational solutions, throughout a typical day and everything they did was recorded in order to get a detailed understanding of their work processes and work environment. The duration of the project lasted eight hours a day, five days a week for four months.\r\n\r\nAccording to de Bruin, when companies implement a training programme and or workshop, many do so following a classroom format whereby supervisors are simply given a training guide and told to study it. “What makes this training programme different is proper on the floor coaching is provided to supervisors to inculcate the on the floor implementation. Supervisors are then assessed to determine what their competency strengths and weaknesses are, and evaluated against these in order to ensure success in the supervisory role.\r\n\r\nDe Bruin says the aim of the project was to optimise labour productivity at the mine in order to increase throughput, by focusing on empowering the supervisors to increase their own productivity. The project also ensured that the supervisors were better equipped to handle day-to-day work by understanding what their full role entails and how to apply that knowledge.\r\nThe results of the project showed that the competencies of the supervisors increased by an average of 10%, while planning and execution competencies increased by 30%. As a result production output improved between 15% and 25% over the four months.\r\n\r\n“These results show a directly link between the intervention’s effectiveness and increased output. We believe the success of the pilot can be ascribed to the unique combination of defining the required competencies, converting them into operational measurements and efficiencies, and practical on-the-job coaching support by workshop training, assignment and on-going assessments.”\r\n\r\nDe Bruin says these the results highlight the importance of the training as it not only impacts the supervisors by making them more efficient, but also empowers them to manage their teams more effectively and increase the workforce productivity in the long-term,” concludes de Bruin.', 'Warning of a tough 2013 on labour front', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'warning-of-a-tough-2013-on-labour-front', '', '', '2013-11-11 11:42:00', '2013-11-11 09:42:00', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=947', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(948, 3, '2013-10-25 20:52:31', '2013-10-25 18:52:31', '<strong>Featured on:</strong> <a href="http://www.gbn.co.za" target="_blank">Gauteng Business News</a>\r\n\r\nBUSINESS: Supervisors Are the Key to Productivity\r\nSouth Africa’s labour productivity has reached a 46-year low according to recent Adcorp figures. This figure can be attributed to a major gap across all South African industries, whereby supervisors lack efficient training and are not properly equipped with the right skillset to fulfill their role.\r\n\r\nThis is the view of Arjen de Bruin, Operations Solutions MD at OIM International - a leading business consultancy firm, who says companies are able to improve productivity levels by an average of 10% to 15%, by ensuring that supervisors receive practical on the floor coaching with relevant training to help them fully understand their role as the drivers of sustainable workforce productivity.\r\n\r\n“The biggest impact on a workforce is the supervisor, as he or she is responsible for managing all processes, removing obstacles and assessing overall workforce productivity. Supervisors therefore need to possess efficient problem solving techniques, plan correctly and be able to communicate daily tasks effectively to the team as these skills are critical for ensuring workforce throughput,” says de Bruin.\r\n\r\nDe Bruins says 80% of a supervisor’s time should be spent ensuring the team is maximizing production output thoroughly each day. “Instead, what we find is that 60% of the time supervisors are busy with passive supervision, admin or HR-related duties and getting involved in production, as there is often a skills deficit and the supervisor has no other choice but to fill the gap. We have also noticed the supervisor fall into a comfort zone with work that is familiar.” \r\n\r\nDe Bruin argues that by working on a supervisor’s key competences, where he plans his day correctly, communicates tasks effectively to his team, takes care of his staff, remove obstacles through problem solving, develops his staff where there are skills lacking; he will become more efficient in carrying out tasks and be able to increase business production.\r\n\r\n“These competencies are the basis of a supervisor’s role and it is therefore important that enough time is invested training supervisors to ensure that they understand them and to ensure they are equipped with the necessary skills. However it is important to note that the time invested in improving people’s skills, must be reflected in increased output and quality. Moreover, by implementing constant performance feedback and measurement, performance will be optimised across the business.”\r\n\r\nDe Bruin says when supervisors and their labour force are provided with structure, alignment and focus in their day-to-day activities, individuals will have a shared purpose and direction of their role. Similarly, for supervisor to be effective leaders, consistent communication and engagement needs to happen in order for them to understand how their roles contribute to the success of the company.\r\n\r\nThese key disciplines need to be integrated into a training programme that combines practical on-the-floor coaching and continuous assessments. De Bruin refers to a pilot project that used this training programme on a South African mine, conducted by OIM International earlier this year. All supervisors of the mine were assigned experienced operational improvement consultants and underwent intense training, on-the-floor coaching and practical assessments. Supervisors were observed, coached and together with the consultant co-created operational solutions, throughout a typical day and everything they did was recorded in order to get a detailed understanding of their work processes and work environment. The duration of the project lasted eight hours a day, five days a week for four months. \r\n\r\nAccording to de Bruin, when companies implement a training programme and or workshop, many do so following a classroom format whereby supervisors are simply given a training guide and told to study it. “What makes this training programme different is proper on the floor coaching is provided to supervisors to inculcate the on the floor implementation. Supervisors are then assessed to determine what their competency strengths and weaknesses are, and evaluated against these in order to ensure success in the supervisory role. \r\n\r\nDe Bruin says the aim of the project was to optimise labour productivity at the mine in order to increase throughput, by focusing on empowering the supervisors to increase their own productivity. The project also ensured that the supervisors were better equipped to handle day-to-day work by understanding what their full role entails and how to apply that knowledge.\r\nThe results of the project showed that the competencies of the supervisors increased by an average of 10%, while planning and execution competencies increased by 30%. As a result production output improved between 15% and 25% over the four months. \r\n\r\n“These results show a directly link between the intervention’s effectiveness and increased output. We believe the success of the pilot can be ascribed to the unique combination of defining the required competencies, converting them into operational measurements and efficiencies, and practical on-the-job coaching support by workshop training, assignment and on-going assessments.”\r\n\r\nDe Bruin says these the results highlight the importance of the training as it not only impacts the supervisors by making them more efficient, but also empowers them to manage their teams more effectively and increase the workforce productivity in the long-term,” concludes de Bruin. ', 'Warning of a tough 2013 on labour front', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '947-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-25 20:52:31', '2013-10-25 18:52:31', '', 947, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/news/uncategorized/947-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(949, 3, '2012-12-08 20:52:36', '2012-12-08 18:52:36', 'Bloemfontein. – Werksoekers wat in 2013 die ander aansoekers wil uitstof, moenie slegs op ’n indrukwekkende lys kwalifikasies staatmaak nie.\r\n\r\nVerskeie kundiges en werkgewers met wie Sake24 gepraat het, beklemtoon daar is deesdae nuwe ‘moet-hê-vaardighede’ in die werkplek. Dit was opmerklik dat leierskap en selfhandhawing deur verskeie kenners hoog aangeslaan is – selfs vir die laagste range.\r\n\r\n“Elke mens het die vermoë om te lei, en as jy jou eie sterk punte en tekortkominge ken, sal jy groei as mens en as leier; tot voordeel van jouself en jou organisasie,” sê Deirdre Elphick-Moore, medestigter van The Office Coach.\r\n\r\nHierby voeg sy die vermoë om jouself verantwoordbaar te hou.\r\n\r\n“Jy as werknemer het ’n impak op jou sukses of mislukking, asook op die welstand van jou onderneming. Almal in die werkplek behoort hierdie uitgangspunt te deel sodat maatskappye en gemeenskappe kan gedy.”\r\n\r\nDaar is deesdae groot klem op multidissiplinêre spanwerk in organisasies, sê Tjaart Minnaar, besturende direkteur van OIM International, ’n sake-konsultant wat onder meer in die ontwikkeling van leierskap en prestasie spesialiseer. Spanwerk verg leiers op alle vlakke van ’n organisasie.\r\n\r\n“Elkeen in ’n organisasie moet kan voorloop as dit nodig is, en as jy nie ’n leier op jou terrein word nie, sal iemand anders dit in jou plek word.”\r\n\r\nNog ’n belangrike vaardigheid is die vermoë om jou in ’n ander werknemer se skoene te kan plaas.\r\n\r\n“In Suid-Afrika het ons al ver gevorder om kulturele diversiteit in die werkplek te verstaan.\r\n\r\n“Ons vaar minder goed met funksionele diversiteit. Dit is die vermoë van werknemers in verskillende afdelings in ’n maatskappy om empatie met mekaar se uitgangspunte en prioriteite te hê,” sê hy.\r\n\r\nAs voorbeeld noem hy daar is dikwels konflik tussen afdelings soos bemarking en finansiële bestuur omdat hulle verskillende doelwitte nastreef. Aanpasbaarheid, buigsaamheid en die vermoë om vinnig nuwe tegnologie onder die knie te kry, is ook hoog op die meeste kundiges se lysie.\r\n\r\nDie werkplek het die afgelope jare dramaties verander. Dit beteken werknemers moet hulself voortdurend verder bekwaam, sê Lyndy van den Barselaar, besturende direkteur van die werwingsgroep Manpower. Sy wys daarop dat voortdurende verandering beteken werknemers moet soms mekaar se take oorneem.\r\n\r\n“In die huidige moeilike ekonomiese omstandighede oorleef ondernemings deur die werk onder ’n kleiner groep werknemers te verdeel. Indien jy maklik aanpas by verandering, en boonop maklik opleibaar is, is jy in aanvraag.”\r\n\r\nSaam met aanpasbaarheid kom die vermoë om te innoveer, sê Charles Stretch, besturende direkteur van SMSPortal.\r\n\r\n“Maatskappye soek veral na mense wat vinnig snap wat van hulle verwag word, en die struikelblokke kan oorkom. Dis hierdie soort aanpasbaarheid en moed wat spanne en organisasies dryf om te innoveer en die mededingers verby te steek.”\r\n\r\nWerknemers wat innoveer en geleenthede skep, is geweldig waardevol vir hul maatskappye, beaam Natalie Maroun, hoofstrateeg by LRMG.\r\n\r\n“Beste praktyk verander gedurig en dit vereis mense wat gedrewe voel om te ontdek en om meer te leer sodat hulle aan die voorpunt van verandering bly.”\r\n\r\nJy sal nie mededingend in die werkplek bly as jy nie voortdurend byhou met die jongste IKT-vaardighede nie, waarsku sy.\r\n\r\n“Nuwe ontwikkelings soos wolkverwerking beteken dat kantoorwerk toenemend in die virtuele wêreld gedoen word. Jy kan dus in die omgewing van jou keuse werk – maar die regte IKT-vaardighede is die sleutel tot dié proses.”\r\n\r\nVerskeie werkgewers het egter ook gewys op leemtes wat hulle in veral jonger werksoekers se mondering sien.\r\n\r\n“Werkgewers soek ’n eienskap wat ek ‘professionaliteit’ sal noem,” sê dr. Erika Wassenaar, ontwikkelingsbestuurder by Business Partners. Dit behels ’n netjiese en afgeronde voorkoms, maar ook om met aandag en empatie te luister na kliënte, om kollegas in ag te neem en die werkplek op ’n hoflike wyse met hulle te deel, sê sy.\r\n\r\n“Dis iemand wat bereid is om meer as die gewone te doen, en wat besef kliënte betaal sy salaris en is dus geregtig op sy beste diens.”\r\n\r\nKekeletso Khena, direkteur van die Tomorrow’s Leaders Conven¬tion, ’n organisasie wat maatskappye bystaan om uitvoerende talent te identifiseer en op te lei, sê die grootste leemte is ’n gebrek aan doodgewone gesonde verstand.\r\n\r\n“Ek definieer dit as die kognitiewe vermoë om intuïtief te weet wat die regte ding is om te doen en dit te doen. Dít is die eienskap wat iemand laat uitstaan bo ander wat dieselfde intellektuele of tegniese vaardighede het.”\r\n\r\nLaaste maar nie die minste nie, is ’n sin vir humor en ’n positiewe uitkyk op die lewe ’n eienskap wat werkgewers hoog op prys stel.\r\n\r\n“Optimisme is die bes bewaarde geheim in die werkplek.\r\n\r\n“Dis ’n emosionele bevoegdheid wat produktiwiteit opstoot, moreel verhoog, konflik ontlont en ’n wesenlike invloed op sukses kan hê,” sê Stretch.', 'Moet-hê-vaardighede vir 2013', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'moet-he-vaardighede-vir-2013', '', '', '2013-11-11 11:41:37', '2013-11-11 09:41:37', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=949', 0, 'post', '', 0);
